<body>

  <nav>
    <a href="/" class="nav-home">// ROOT</a>
    <span class="nav-sep">/</span>
    <a href="/professional" class="nav-home">PROFESSIONAL</a>
    <span class="nav-sep">/</span>
    <a href="/blog" class="nav-home">FIELD NOTES</a>
    <span class="nav-sep">/</span>
    <span class="nav-current">AVI IN VCF</span>
  </nav>

  <div class="article-wrap">

    <header class="article-header">
      <div class="article-tags">
        {tags.map(tag => <span class="tag">#{tag}</span>)}
      </div>
      <h1 class="article-title">{title}</h1>
      <div class="article-meta">
        <span class="meta-item">{date}</span>
        <span class="meta-sep">//</span>
        <span class="meta-item">{readTime} read</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">

      <p>
        There's a conversation I have regularly with customers who are deep into VCF. They've got
        DFW running, they've got NSX segments laid out, maybe they're starting to look at vDefend SSP.
        And then I ask about their load balancer.
      </p>

      <p>
        Nine times out of ten, the answer is something like: an F5 pair in hardware, or an HAProxy VM
        someone stood up two years ago, or a pair of appliances that predate the VCF deployment entirely.
        When I point out that AVI is included in their VCF license and has been sitting there since day
        one, the response is almost always the same: <em>"We knew it was there. We just never touched it."</em>
      </p>

      <p>
        This post is about what AVI actually is, how it fits into a VCF environment, and the practical
        path from "it's installed somewhere" to "it's routing production traffic."
      </p>

      <h2>// What AVI Actually Is</h2>

      <p>
        AVI is a software-defined application delivery controller — an ADC. Not a load balancer
        bolted onto an existing product. It was purpose-built by Avi Networks before VMware acquired
        them, and the architecture reflects that: the control plane is separated from the data plane,
        the data plane scales elastically, and everything is managed through a modern API.
      </p>

      <p>
        The three things you need to understand to work with AVI are the <strong>Controller</strong>,
        the <strong>Service Engines</strong>, and the <strong>Virtual Services</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="diagram">
        <div><span class="label">// AVI ARCHITECTURE</span></div>
        <div>&nbsp;</div>
        <div><span class="node">[ AVI Controller ]</span>  <span class="label">← management plane, API, analytics</span></div>
        <div>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="arrow">↓</span></div>
        <div><span class="node">[ Service Engine 1 ]</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="node">[ Service Engine 2 ]</span>  <span class="label">← data plane VMs, auto-deployed</span></div>
        <div>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="arrow">↓</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="arrow">↓</span></div>
        <div><span class="node">[ Pool: App Server 1 ]</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="node">[ Pool: App Server 2 ]</span>  <span class="label">← your backends</span></div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The <strong>Controller</strong> is a three-node cluster (or single node in lab) that handles
        all configuration, analytics, and orchestration. It talks to vCenter and NSX — it knows your
        inventory, it can place Service Engines automatically, and it feeds telemetry into a built-in
        analytics engine that most customers don't realize is there.
      </p>

      <p>
        The <strong>Service Engines (SEs)</strong> are VMs that the Controller deploys automatically
        when you create a Virtual Service. They live on your ESXi hosts, they scale out when load
        increases, and they scale back when it drops. You don't provision them manually. The Controller
        handles placement based on HA settings and host capacity. This is the piece that surprises most
        people coming from hardware LBs — you stop thinking about individual appliances and start
        thinking about capacity pools.
      </p>

      <p>
        A <strong>Virtual Service</strong> is the entity that represents your application endpoint.
        It has a VIP, a port, a protocol, an application profile, and a pool. The pool is your list
        of backend servers with health monitors. That's the core unit you'll create and manage.
      </p>

      <h2>// What It Does That Hardware Doesn't</h2>

      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-cell">
          <div class="feature-cell-label">Real-Time Analytics</div>
          <p>Per-connection, per-client, per-pool member metrics. End-to-end visibility from VIP to backend without a separate monitoring tool.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-cell">
          <div class="feature-cell-label">Elastic Scale</div>
          <p>Service Engines scale out under load automatically. You set the SE group parameters once. No manual capacity planning for traffic spikes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-cell">
          <div class="feature-cell-label">Built-In WAF</div>
          <p>OWASP CRS-based WAF included. Not a bolt-on. Configured per Virtual Service with learning mode so you don't break apps on day one.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-cell">
          <div class="feature-cell-label">SSL/TLS Offload</div>
          <p>Full SSL termination and re-encryption. Certificate management through the Controller. SNI support. HSM integration available.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-cell">
          <div class="feature-cell-label">NSX Integration</div>
          <p>AVI pools can use NSX security groups as members. Your server inventory is dynamic — add a server to the right group, AVI picks it up.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-cell">
          <div class="feature-cell-label">API-First</div>
          <p>Everything in the UI is an API call. Full Terraform provider. GitOps-friendly configuration. Infrastructure-as-code for app delivery.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>// The Gap TAMs See in the Field</h2>

      <p>
        The pattern isn't that customers haven't deployed AVI — it's that they deployed the
        Controller, stood up a few Virtual Services for an internal app or two, and stopped
        there. The hardware appliances stayed in place for anything production-critical because
        "that's what we trust."
      </p>

      <p>
        The result: AVI is doing a fraction of what it's capable of, and the hardware LBs are
        handling production workloads that AVI could handle better — with more visibility and
        less operational overhead. The TAM conversation usually ends with: <em>"You're paying
        maintenance on those appliances. You already own AVI. What's the migration plan?"</em>
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-label">// Field Note</div>
        <p>
          The most common blocker isn't technical — it's trust. Engineers who've run hardware
          LBs for a decade are skeptical of a software ADC managing production traffic. The
          right approach is to start with net-new applications rather than trying to migrate
          existing ones. Let AVI prove itself on a greenfield workload, build familiarity, then
          look at migration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>// Getting Started: The Actual Path</h2>

      <p>
        Assuming AVI is already deployed in your VCF environment (check under the Workload
        Management section in vCenter, or in the VCF SDDC Manager), here's the path from
        "installed" to "routing traffic":
      </p>

      <ol class="step-list">
        <li>
          <span class="step-num">01</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Connect AVI to vCenter and NSX.</strong> In the AVI Controller UI
            (<code>https://&lt;controller-ip&gt;</code>), go to Infrastructure → Clouds.
            Your VCF deployment should already have a cloud configured. Verify the vCenter
            and NSX-T credentials are active and the status shows green. If not, re-enter
            credentials — these often expire after password rotations.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-num">02</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Configure a Service Engine Group.</strong> This defines where your SEs
            will be placed, the HA model, and the max SE count. For production, use N+1
            HA with a minimum of two SEs. For testing, a single SE is fine. Go to
            Infrastructure → Service Engine Groups → Default-Group and verify it points
            at the right vSphere cluster.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-num">03</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Create a Pool.</strong> Applications → Pools → Create. Add your backend
            server IPs and port, select a health monitor (HTTP or HTTPS for web apps, TCP
            for everything else). AVI will start health-checking immediately after save.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-num">04</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Create a Virtual Service.</strong> Applications → Virtual Services →
            Basic Setup. Assign your VIP address, select the pool you just created, choose
            an application profile (HTTP, HTTPS, L4), and save. AVI will deploy Service
            Engines automatically if none exist in the SE Group. First-time SE deployment
            takes 2–4 minutes.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-num">05</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Verify in the Analytics tab.</strong> Once the Virtual Service is up,
            click into it and go to Analytics. You'll see real-time connection counts,
            latency to pool members, and end-to-end response times. This alone is worth
            the migration from a hardware box — the visibility is dramatically better.
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>// Sizing Reality Check</h2>

      <p>
        Service Engines are VMs. By default they're sized at 2 vCPU / 2 GB RAM. In most
        environments that's fine for internal workloads, but if you're moving high-throughput
        production traffic — large SSL offload, heavy L7 inspection — you'll want to adjust
        the SE flavor in the SE Group settings before you create Virtual Services. Changing
        the SE size after the fact requires deleting and recreating the SE VMs.
      </p>

      <p>
        Also: AVI Controller resources. The Controller cluster runs on VMs too — default
        sizing is 8 vCPU / 24 GB RAM per node. Don't deploy it on a cluster that's already
        memory-constrained. In several field deployments I've seen the Controller degraded
        not from load, but from vSphere memory pressure causing balloon activity on Controller
        VMs. Reserve memory at the VM level if you're tight on resources.
      </p>

      <h2>// Where This Fits in the VCF Stack</h2>

      <p>
        Think of your VCF security posture in layers. DFW handles east-west access control —
        who can talk to what. vDefend SSP and ATP handle threat detection and inline prevention
        — identifying and blocking malicious traffic at the hypervisor level. AVI sits at the
        application tier: it's the intelligent front door for your workloads, handling traffic
        distribution, SSL, and application-layer protection through WAF.
      </p>

      <p>
        These aren't competing tools. They're complementary. A properly layered VCF environment
        uses all three: NSX DFW for segmentation, vDefend for threat prevention, and AVI for
        application delivery. Most customers I work with have the first one running well, are
        in progress on the second, and haven't touched the third.
      </p>

    </div>

    <div class="closing-callout">
      <p>
        If you're a TAM or SE reading this: the AVI conversation is usually easiest to open
        when a customer mentions a hardware LB renewal. That's the moment to ask what's in
        their VCF license and whether they've looked at AVI for net-new workloads. The renewal
        math plus the functionality gap usually gets the conversation started.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you're an engineer reading this: start with one non-critical application and spend
        an hour in the Analytics tab. Once you see what per-connection visibility looks like
        on a modern software ADC, it's hard to go back to a hardware box with SNMP polling.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>

  <footer>
    <span class="footer-label">// THE SEGMENTED NERD</span>
    <span class="footer-label">thesegmentednerd.com</span>
  </footer>

</body>
